{{for|the Malayalam film actress|Rani Chandra}} {{not to be confused with|The Rani (Doctor Who)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{DISPLAYTITLE:Rani Chandra (''The Sarah Jane Adventures'')}} {{Infobox Doctor Who character | image = [[Image:RaniSJA.png|200px]] | name = Rani Chandra |series= ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' | affiliation = *[[Sarah Jane Smith]] *[[Luke Smith (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|Luke Smith]] *[[Clyde Langer]] *[[Maria Jackson]] *[[Tenth Doctor]] *[[Eleventh Doctor]] *[[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart]] *[[Jo Grant]] *[[Sky Smith]] | race = [[Human]]| | planet = [[Earth]]| | era = Early 21st century | start = ''[[The Day of the Clown]]'' | finish =''[[The Man Who Never Was (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|The Man Who Never Was]]'' | portrayer =[[Anjli Mohindra]] }}
'''Rani Chandra''' is a fictional character played by [[Anjli Mohindra]] in the British [[children's television|children's]] [[science fiction television]] programme ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'', a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from the long-running series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. She first appeared in ''[[The Day of the Clown]]''.
==Conception== Rani Chandra was introduced into ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'' as a replacement for departing character [[Maria Jackson]] played by [[Yasmin Paige]]. Paige left the series as a regular due to her wanting to complete her GCSE's, thus, Maria moved to America because her Dad had been offered a job there.<ref name="SFX interview">{{cite web | url = http://www.sfx.co.uk/page/sfx?entry=new_rani_interviewed | title = New Rani interviewed! | date = 29 August 2008 | accessdate = 4 September 2008 | last = Berriman | first = Ian | work = [[SFX magazine|SFX]]}}</ref> Rani's parents, [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Haresh Chandra|Haresh]] and [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Gita Chandra|Gita Chandra]], replace Maria's parents, [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Alan Jackson|Alan]] and [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Chrissie Jackson|Chrissie Jackson]], as Alan departs with their daughter and Chrissie no longer has reason to show up.<ref name="Blog to be replaced with the DWM source it quotes when I've dug my copy out">{{cite web | url = http://sarahjanetv.blogspot.com/2008/08/comings-goings.html | title = Comings & Goings | date = 20 August 2008 | accessdate = 4 September 2008 | publisher = SARAH-JANE.tv}}</ref><ref name="Digital Spy">{{cite web |url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/cult/a127526/cult-spy-autumn-preview.html | title = Cult Spy: Autumn Preview | date = 2008-08-31 | accessdate = 2008-09-04 | publisher = [[Digital Spy]] | last = Rawson-Jones | first = Ben}}</ref>
Rani shares her name with [[The Rani (Doctor Who)|the Rani]], a recurring villain from the classic series of ''[[Doctor Who]]''. [[Russell T Davies]] told readers of ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' that Rani is "not ''the'' Rani".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Davies |first=Russell T |authorlink=Russell T Davies |date=15 October 2008 |title=Further Investigation! |journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |issue=400 |pages=53 |publisher=[[Panini Publishing]] |location=[[Tunbridge Wells]]}}</ref>
==Appearances== Rani Chandra first appears in the second story of series two, replacing the character of [[Maria Jackson]] ([[Yasmin Paige]]). In ''[[The Day of the Clown]]'' (2008), Rani and her parents move into the Jacksons' old house at 12 Bannerman Road<ref>''The Invasion of the Bane''</ref> (sometimes 36 Bannerman Road<ref>''The Last Sontaran''</ref>), opposite [[Sarah Jane Smith|Sarah Jane]] ([[Elisabeth Sladen]]) and [[Luke Smith (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|Luke Smith]]'s ([[Tommy Knight]]) house, in [[Ealing]], [[London]].<ref name="SFX interview"/> Her father is the new head teacher of the school where she, Luke and his best friend [[Clyde Langer|Clyde]] ([[Daniel Anthony (actor)|Daniel Anthony]]) are pupils; her mother owns Bloomin' Lovely floral shop. An aspiring journalist, Rani soon joins Sarah Jane's investigative gang.<ref name="SFX interview"/><ref name="Digital Spy"/><ref name="Official website">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sja/sites/mrsmith/noflash/personal_data/?video=rani|title=Rani Chandra|accessdate=2008-09-04|publisher=[[BBC]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130419201230/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cbbc/directories/the-sarah-jane-adventures-characters-and-aliens|archivedate=19 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
In the series three première ''[[Prisoner of the Judoon]]'' (2009), Rani and Clyde are banned by extraterrestrial police force the [[Judoon]] from space travel as punishment for interference in their work.<ref>"[[Prisoner of the Judoon]]" part 2</ref> Although grounded on her terrestrial homeworld, she is nobility of an unspecified alien planet. A humanoid child monarch known as Gavin creates her Lady Rani in appreciation of her assistance in his succession which also saved the whole of humanity.<ref>''[[The Empty Planet]]'' part 2</ref> Coincidentally, she is continually addressed as Lady Rani in the subsequent serial, when she is transported to the court of [[Lady Jane Grey|Queen Jane]] and mistaken for a newly summoned lady-in-waiting.<ref>''[[Lost in Time (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|Lost in Time]]''</ref>
Series three story ''[[The Mad Woman in the Attic]]'' focuses on Rani. Sarah Jane discovers that, in violation of her rules, Rani has shared her adventures in letters to her former schoolfriend Samuel; the events of the episode cause two timelines to occur, one where in 2059, Rani has acquired the Smith home at 13 Bannerman Road and become miserable and alone, and another where she will have a son and grandchildren and still friends with Luke and even her predecessor, Maria, living with her family at the former Smith home. Rani's final appearance comes in series five, in the last episode of the programme, ''[[The Man Who Never Was (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|The Man Who Never Was]]'' (2011).
==Characterisation== The official ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'' website offers the following description of Rani Chandra:
{{cquote|''15, inquisitive, smart and sassy. Wants to be a [[journalist]], a sort of junior Sarah Jane, and thus idolises Sarah Jane just a little and in return, Sarah Jane takes her happily on her investigations. Rani enjoys Luke's company because they're both quite bright and eager to learn. However, she's equally fond of [[Clyde Langer|Clyde]] because he's cool and a bit rebellious, and has charm.'' |200|50|-[[CBBC]] ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'' website<ref name="Official website"/>}}
In an interview for ''[[SFX magazine|SFX]]'', Mohindra asserts that Rani and Maria are only similar in the extent that they are both girls, live in the same house and "[i]n personality terms...[they are] both quite strong-willed", although she notes that there are "a lot less tears from Rani than there were from Maria." She describes Rani's relationship with Sarah Jane as "a lot different" to that between Sarah Jane and Maria. Mohindra notes that Rani is "very much an apprentice of Sarah Jane...[although] at first...Sarah Jane is not really that interested in taking on another child." Rani [[Job Shadow|shadows]] Sarah Jane and copies her behaviour to help her deal with a situation. She is keen on [[Psychological warfare|fighting mentally]] as opposed to [[Assault|physically]] and Mohindra likes the fact that Rani is "a girl between two guys at times".<ref name="SFX interview"/>
==Reception== Reviewing the second series of ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'' for [[Digital Spy]], Ben Rawson-Jones writes that: "As Rani, Anjli Mohindra was fine with dialogue, but painfully self-conscious on a physical acting level when compared to the effortless ease with which [[Daniel Anthony (actor)|Daniel Anthony]] and [[Tommy Knight]] portray Clyde and Luke. It was almost as if someone was stood slightly off set operating her with strings. That theory at least fits into the whole 'body possession' procession of the second season."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/cult/a138218/sarah-jane-season-two-the-cult-spy-verdict.html|title= 'Sarah Jane' Season Two: The Verdict|last=Rawson-Jones|first=Ben|date=14 December 2008|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>
Following Rani’s first appearance, Michael Bush writes for Den Of Geek: “Rani is another asset to the fledgling cast: a gabby young journalist whose inquisitive nature leads to a run in with alien foes. Comparisons between Rani and Sarah Jane's former companion [[Maria Jackson|Maria]] are almost inevitable, and bound to be divisive, but - based on this episode, at least - Mohindra gives as good as she takes, and her character manages to be interesting and endearing without treading on Miss Jackson's toes.” <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/9054/the-sarah-jane-adventures-series-2-episode-3-review|title=The Sarah Jane Adventures series 2 episode 3 review|last=|first=|date=|work=Den of Geek|access-date=2018-02-20|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|publisher=|language=en}}</ref>
